\subsection{Radiative heat transfer analysis of 37-pin fuel bundle of Indian pressurized heavy water reactor under heat-up condition: experimental, numerical and analytical study}
This research analyzes radiative heat transfer in a 37-pin fuel bundle of an Indian Pressurized Heavy Water Reactor (PHWR) under heat-up conditions, specifically during a Loss of Coolant Accident (LOCA) coupled with Emergency Core Cooling System (ECCS) failure. The study employs experimental, numerical (ANSYS Fluent 19.0), and analytical (radiosity network method) techniques, finding good agreement between them. Results indicate a radial temperature gradient in the fuel bundle simulator (FBS) and insignificant circumferential temperature gradients in the FBS, Pressure Tube (PT), and Calandria Tube (CT).\par

\subsection{Scale-resolving simulations of the flow in a nuclear fuel bundle with a channel spacer grid using partially averaged Navier–Stokes and large-eddy simulation}
This paper evaluates the Partially Averaged Navier–Stokes (PANS) method for simulating flow in a nuclear fuel bundle with a spacer grid. The PANS model's ability to bridge between RANS and DNS is investigated by varying filter cutoff parameters. The study compares PANS results with URANS, LES, and experimental data, analyzing flow statistics, pressure drop, and turbulence anisotropy to determine PANS's suitability for this application.\par

\subsection{Modeling and Visualization of Coolant Flow in a Fuel Rod Bundle of a Small Modular Reactor}
This paper presents experimental results on coolant flow in a small modular reactor's fuel rod bundle. Using an aerodynamic model and airflow based on hydrodynamic similarity, researchers employed pneumometric and contrast agent injection methods to visualize and determine flow characteristics. The study identified features of axial flow and the structure of cross-flows, contributing a valuable database for CFD validation and thermal-hydraulic calculations.\par

\subsection{Volumetric Measurements of Mean Velocity Vector and Reynolds Stress Tensor for CFD Validation: Magnetic Resonance Velocimetry in a Nuclear Fuel Assembly Model with Mixing Grids}
This study presents a new Magnetic Resonance Velocimetry (MRV) method to obtain high-accuracy, three-dimensional volumetric measurements of mean velocity vectors and the Reynolds stress tensor in a 5x5 nuclear fuel assembly model. The data, collected in an OECD/NEA-KAERI rod bundle benchmark exercise, aims to validate computational fluid dynamics (CFD) models for nuclear reactor simulations. The measurements cover a significant downstream region from the mixing grid, with reported uncertainties of 1.9\% for velocity and 0.7-1.8\% for Reynolds stresses.\par

\subsection{Features of the coolant flow in the fuel rod bundle of the fuel assembly of the RITM reactor of a nuclear icebreaker}
This paper presents experimental results on the coolant flow characteristics within the fuel rod bundle of a RITM reactor fuel assembly for a nuclear icebreaker.  The study utilized a scale model to investigate hydrodynamic features, visualizing axial and tangential flow velocities to identify flow patterns and transverse currents. The findings are intended to inform fuel rod bundle design and serve as validation data for CFD programs and thermohydraulic calculation methods.\par

\subsection{Numerical study of the fuel rod melting and molten material migration behavior using the MPS method}
This study numerically investigates fuel rod melting and molten material migration during nuclear reactor core meltdowns using the moving particle semi-implicit (MPS) method. The research develops a 3D MPS code incorporating heat transfer, eutectic reactions, and surface tension models to simulate complex phenomena like phase changes and fluid dynamics. Validation against analytical solutions and FROMA experiments confirms the code's accuracy in predicting temperature responses and phase transitions, with simulations of both substitute materials and actual reactor rods revealing significant influences of atomic diffusion, radiation heat transfer, and molten pool depth on melting behavior and material migration.\par

